I think the issue comes to light on matters which are important, and
then is used to wield power over matters which are not.

People should not be discriminated against in any way because of their
religion, ethnic background, or sexual preference, even if you disagree
with or dislike said religion, preference, ethnicity. This is a
tolerance issue which is important.

Schools should NOT be forced to remove Christmas decorations because it
offended someone. This is not tolerance, this is oppression. Someone
mentioned earlier they believed this to be an establishment clause
issue. I disagree. Christmas is a secularized holiday with a purely
commercial front that is an American tradition. Allowing Christmas
trees does not in any way make a law respecting an establishment of
religion, or prohibiting the free exercise thereof. &quot;Tolerance&quot; has
been the basis for many &quot;freedom from offense&quot; actions that do nothing
to make our society better. The establishment clause has been used to
seek out freedom FROM religion. The two combined have given us Public
Offices where Christmas and Hannukah are outlawed, and Kwaanza is
welcome.

It may be legal, it may have some strict interprative basis in law, but
it's not right.

