Lee,
If the personal religion of the the members of a government make the
government biased, can you explain to me how we could have a government
which is not biased? Whether you practice theism, agnosticism, or
atheism, you are going to have a bias inherent to that belief set. It
is impossible for a government without bias to exist, unless of course
we turn over power to the machines. The founders of the US were all
very religious, but recognized the dangers inherent in having a true
theocracy, as evidenced by the history of both the Catholic and
Anglican Churches's influence on the governments of Western Europe.
This is why the constitution of the US guarantees both freedom to
practice any form of religion, and forbids legislating in favor of a
specific religion. It does not mean that religion has no place in the
democratic process. The voters who are religious will certainly vote in
line with their religious doctrine and morality, so even if you forbid
politicians from using the word God in some abominable
misinterpretation of the seperation clause, you would still not
eliminate the influence of religion on government. Considering the UK
has its share of religious politicians, I don't think there is real
backing for this bit of humor, except to elicit a giggle, which it did.

